title: Unit Testing in C++
---
Recently I&#39;ve been working on my new [rendering engine](https://github.com/Spaceman1701/RenderingEngine). It&#39;s really the first big C++ project I&#39;ve even taken on, and as such I&#39;m learning how to manage the project as I go. I realized early on that I would need unit tests in to ensure I could actually locate and diagnose bugs. I&#39;ve dabbled in unit testing in Java before (see my sadly unfinished [poker engine](https://github.com/Spaceman1701/MonteCarloPoker)), but never for C or C++. This post will document my experience setting up unit tests for C++.

 My initial research revealed a bunch of different unit testing frameworks to C++, but none of them seemed like the defacto choice. This was a bit overwhelming for me.  Lucky for me, I am using Visual Studio 15 for development which has a built in unit testing framework. I decided to use this framework for a couple reasons. First, it was by far the most convenient framework, as it was included with my installation of Visual Studio. In addition to that, it seems very well integrated into visual studio, which makes it much simpler to use.

After deciding to try Visual Studio&#39;s framework, I naturally went to [MSDN](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh598953.aspx)to learn how to set it up and use it. Unfortunately the instruction are for DLL projects, and my Rendering Engine project is an executable. This didn&#39;t turn out to be that much of a problem, however. My first thought was to create a new configuration for my project that had it compile as a dll or a lib and then run the tests on that version. First, however, I decided to do some research to see if there were any better solutions. I came across this [Stack Overflow post](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/14010627/unresolved-externals-when-compiling-unit-tests-for-visual-c-2012), which was very helpful.

The first thing I did was create a new Native Unit Test Project in visual studio. I configured it to be part of RenderingEngine&#39;s solution. Conveniently, Visual Studio automatically created ```stdafx.h```, ```targetver.h``` and ``unittest1.cpp``` . The ```unittest1.cpp``` already had the following code in it:

{% highlight c++ %}
#include &quot;stdafx.h&quot;

#include &quot;CppUnitTest.h&quot;

using namespace Microsoft::VisualStudio::CppUnitTestFramework;

namespace testUnitTest

{

 TEST\_CLASS(UnitTest1)

 {

 public:

  TEST\_METHOD(TestMethod1)

  {

   // TODO: Your test code here

  }

 };

}
{% endhighlight %}

This is the basic structure for writing unit tests.

After this I just had had to create a new configuration (which I called &quot;Test&quot;) in the properties of the RenderingEngine project:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

I simply changed the &quot;Configuration Type&quot; from executable to static library.

Next I had to configure the unit testing.

First I had added the source directory of the RenderingEngine project as to the unit test project&#39;s &quot;Additional Include Directories&quot; in the linker configuration so that I could include files from the rendering engine. Next I added the output folder for the &quot;Test&quot; configuration of RenderingEngine as a library directory to the unit test project&#39;s configuration. I then set &quot;RenderingEngine.lib&quot; as a dependency (this could also be done by writing ```#pragma comment(lib, &quot;RenderingEngine.lib&quot;)``` in each file. The last step was to add RenderingEngine as a Reference for the unit test project. This can be done through the &quot;Add Reference&quot; window:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Interestingly, the Stack Overflow post I mentioned previously said that it was necessary to use ```__declspec(dllimport)```  for tests to function, but this doesn&#39;t seem to be true. Since I compile the Rendering Engine project as a .lib I do not need  ```dllimport``` or ```dllexport``` declarations at all (at least, to the best of my knowledge). My unit tests are working fine, and I did some testing without the ```__declspec``` declarations and I couldn&#39;t find a difference. It is possible this could become a problem for me later, as I am not entirely sure I understand all the nuances of what I am doing.

Finally, because my project targets x64, I had to select x64 as the default processor architecture for my unit tests. This can be done from the &quot;Test&quot; dropdown in the Visual Studio toolbar.

After getting everything set up, writing and running tests was easy. Visual studio has a convenient &quot;Test Explorer&quot; panel built in for viewing and navigating the results of test. As you can see, my code seems to check out:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

And that&#39;s all for now! I&#39;m still working on Part 2 of my Illumination Engine Code Review, but I should be posting that soon.
